From the [javadoc][1] of class `java.util.Scanner`
&gt; A `Scanner` breaks its input into tokens using a delimiter pattern, which by default matches whitespace.

&quot;Whitespace&quot; includes space, tab and new-line.

I assume that you enter the value for `courseDuration` and then hit &lt;kbd&gt;ENTER&lt;/kbd&gt;. Method [nextDouble][2] reads the number but not the new-line that is due to you pressing &lt;kbd&gt;ENTER&lt;/kbd&gt;. Hence the following call to `nextLine` reads that new-line as the value for `courseStatus`. Then you think that you are entering a value for `courseStatus` but you are actually entering a value for `courseflag`, since `courseStatus` has been already assigned a value of an empty string. Therefore you think that no value was entered for `courseflag`.

That&#39;s why, in the above &quot;sample run&quot; I enter both `courseDuration` and `courseStatus` on the same line and separate them by a single space.

Alternatively, you can uncomment the `sc.nextLine();` in the above code (as I wrote in my [comment][3]) which will allow you to enter `courseDuration` and `courseStatus` on different lines. Here is a sample run that demonstrates.
```none

